      <!-- Introduction -->
      <section class="intro" aria-labelledby="intro-heading">
        <h2 id="intro-heading">Introduction</h2>
        <p>
          We live in an era of relentless distraction — notifications, deadlines, and the constant
          hum of digital noise. Mindfulness offers a quiet counterpoint: the practice of paying
          deliberate, non-judgmental attention to the present moment. What surprises most people
          is how little time it requires to feel a real difference.
        </p>
        <p>
          This post explores the foundations of mindful living, not as an abstract philosophy
          but as a set of concrete, everyday habits that almost anyone can adopt — regardless of
          how busy life gets.
        </p>

        <blockquote>
          <p>"You can't stop the waves, but you can learn to surf." — Jon Kabat-Zinn</p>
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- Main content -->
      <section aria-labelledby="habits-heading">
        <h2 id="habits-heading">Five Habits Worth Starting Today</h2>
        <p>
          Research in positive psychology and neuroscience consistently shows that small,
          repeated behaviours rewire the brain over time. Here are five evidence-backed habits
          that form the backbone of a mindful lifestyle:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Morning breathwork (5 minutes):</strong> Begin each day with four cycles of
            box breathing — inhale for 4 counts, hold for 4, exhale for 4, hold for 4. It
            activates the parasympathetic nervous system and reduces cortisol before the day
            has even started.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Single-tasking windows:</strong> Set a 25-minute timer and work on one task
            only — phone face-down, notifications silenced. The quality of attention you bring
            to a single task is almost always superior to what you achieve while multitasking.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mindful meals:</strong> Eat at least one meal per day without screens.
            Notice flavours, textures, and fullness cues. This simple act has been linked to
            healthier portion control and greater meal satisfaction.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Gratitude journalling (3 entries):</strong> Before bed, write three specific
            things you are grateful for. Specificity is key — "the smell of rain this afternoon"
            is more powerful than "nature".
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Digital sunset:</strong> Switch off all screens at least 60 minutes before
            sleep. Replace that time with reading, gentle stretching, or simply sitting in
            comfortable silence.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          None of these habits demands a retreat to the Himalayas or hours of free time. They
          slot into the margins of an ordinary day — the gaps most of us already have, but
          rarely use intentionally.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Conclusion -->
      <section aria-labelledby="conclusion-heading">
